<div class="comment-text">
<p>I understand your point here. I think I need to clarify this a bit. I don’t mean to say that evidence should not be examined or a case not taken to trial for fear of tarnishing someone’s reputation. That would be an admittedly horrible take.</p>
<p>What I mean is that people should try to approach the situation in the same way as the justice system, in that we should avoid labeling someone as guilty until the evidence is sufficient to prove otherwise. Even if there were not enough evidence to warrant a trial, or even if there Were a trial which ended in a verdict of “not guilty,” the average person may treat the accused as if they were the convicted. (In fact, many in the field of moral psychology believe that this widespread “just in case” mentality is an adaptive defense mechanism.)</p>
<p>My closing line is an argument against this reflexive mentality. The label of “guilty” is a social penalty, and it should be applied only alongside the legal equivalent.</p>
